{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":78943,"duration_api_ms":77842,"num_turns":13,"result":"Here's a summary of the two-part implementation:\n\n### 1. `DeviceTypeChangedHandler` (already exists ‚Äî your new file)\n\n**Location**: `core_business_v2/ingestion/.../handler/DeviceTypeChangedHandler.java`\n\nThis handler deals with the case where a cached entity has a different type than the incoming request (e.g., `HOST` ‚Üí `USER_HOST_BINDING`). Its flow:\n\n1. **Acquire process lock** ‚Äî type change is a mutating operation\n2. **Re-read from DB** ‚Äî avoids stale-cache races\n3. **Rebuild fingerprint** for the new type\n4. **Update entity** ‚Äî sets new type, fingerprint, resets processing stage to `PENDING`, clears error state, populates `userIdentity` for `USER_HOST_BINDING`\n5. **Update cache** with the refreshed entity\n6. **Re-run state machine** from `PENDING`\n\n### 2. Wiring into `CachedExistingEntityHandler` (the edit I just made)\n\n**Location**: `CachedExistingEntityHandler.java:53-61`\n\nAfter the stale-version check but **before** fingerprint comparison, I added a type-mismatch check:\n\n```java\nEntityType reqType = EntityType.valueOf(req.getEntityType());\nif (e.getType() != reqType) {\n    return deviceTypeChangedHandler.handle(req, e);\n}\n```\n\nThis means `DbExistingEntityHandler` also gets this behavior for free since it delegates to `CachedExistingEntityHandler`.\n\n### Flow diagram\n\n```\nIngestionOrchestrator.process(req)\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ cache HIT  ‚Üí CachedExistingEntityHandler.handle()\n  ‚îÇ                  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ version check (skip stale)\n  ‚îÇ                  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ type mismatch? ‚Üí DeviceTypeChangedHandler  ‚Üê NEW\n  ‚îÇ                  ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ fingerprint comparison ‚Üí FingerprintHandler\n  ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ cache MISS, DB found ‚Üí DbExistingEntityHandler ‚Üí (delegates to above)\n  ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ cache MISS, DB not found ‚Üí NewEntityHandler\n```","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"aac1d42a-7ea9-4e8